# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: screen-space-reflections
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:screen-space-reflections/cube-mapping] The same cube mapping as above rendered as a 3D view.
[src:screen-space-reflections/cube-mapping] In computer graphics, **cube mapping** is a method of environment mapping that uses the six faces of a cube as the map shape.
[src:screen-space-reflections/cube-mapping] The environment is projected onto the sides of a cube and stored as six square textures, or unfolded into six regions of a single texture.
[src:screen-space-reflections/cube-mapping] The cube map is generated by first rendering the scene six times from a viewpoint, with the views defined by a 90 degree view frustum representing each cube face.
[src:screen-space-reflections/cube-mapping] Or if the environment is first considered to be projected onto a sphere, then each face of the cube is its gnomonic projection.
[src:screen-space-reflections/cube-mapping] In the majority of cases, cube mapping is preferred over the older method of sphere mapping because it eliminates many of the problems that are inherent in sphere mapping such as image distortion, viewpoint dependency, and computational inefficiency.
[src:screen-space-reflections/cube-mapping] Also, cube mapping provides a much larger capacity to support real-time rendering of reflections relative to sphere mapping because the combination of inefficiency and viewpoint dependency severely limits the ability of sphere mapping to be applied when there is a consistently changing viewpoint.
[src:screen-space-reflections/cube-mapping] Variants of cube mapping are also commonly used in 360 video projection.
[src:screen-space-reflections/cube-mapping] Cube mapping was first proposed in 1986 by Ned Greene in his paper "Environment Mapping and Other Applications of World Projections", ten years after environment mapping was first put forward by Jim Blinn and Martin Newell.
[src:screen-space-reflections/cube-mapping] However, hardware limitations on the ability to access six texture images simultaneously made it infeasible to implement cube mapping without further technological developments.
[src:screen-space-reflections/cube-mapping] This problem was remedied in 1999 with the release of the Nvidia GeForce 256.
[src:screen-space-reflections/cube-mapping] Nvidia touted cube mapping in hardware as "a breakthrough image quality feature of GeForce 256 that ... will allow developers to create accurate, real-time reflections.
[src:screen-space-reflections/cube-mapping] Cube mapping is preferred over other methods of environment mapping because of its relative simplicity.
[src:screen-space-reflections/cube-mapping] Cube mapping also produces results that are similar to those obtained by ray tracing, but is much more computationally efficient – the moderate reduction in quality is compensated for by large gains in efficiency.
[src:screen-space-reflections/cube-mapping] Pre-dating cube mapping, sphere mapping has many inherent flaws that made it impractical for most applications.
[src:screen-space-reflections/cube-mapping] Sphere mapping is view-dependent, meaning that a different texture is necessary for each viewpoint.
[src:screen-space-reflections/cube-mapping] Therefore, in applications where the viewpoint is mobile, it would be necessary to dynamically generate a new sphere mapping for each new viewpoint (or, to pre-generate a mapping for every viewpoint).
[src:screen-space-reflections/cube-mapping] Also, a texture mapped onto a sphere's surface must be stretched and compressed, and warping and distortion (particularly along the edge of the sphere) are a direct consequence of this.
[src:screen-space-reflections/cube-mapping] Although these image flaws can be reduced using certain tricks and techniques like "pre-stretching", this just adds another layer of complexity to sphere mapping.
[src:screen-space-reflections/cube-mapping] Paraboloid mapping provides some improvement on the limitations of sphere mapping, however it requires two rendering passes in addition to special image warping operations and more involved computation.
[src:screen-space-reflections/cube-mapping] Conversely, cube mapping requires only a single render pass, and due to its simple nature, is very easy for developers to comprehend and generate.
[src:screen-space-reflections/cube-mapping] Also, cube mapping uses the entire resolution of the texture image, compared to sphere and paraboloid mappings, which also allows it to use lower resolution images to achieve the same quality.
[src:screen-space-reflections/cube-mapping] Although handling the seams of the cube map is a problem, algorithms have been developed to handle seam behavior and result in a seamless reflection.
[src:screen-space-reflections/cube-mapping] Disadvantages include discontinuity, a high about of indexing, linear interpolation of vectors (when calculated in hardware), filtering across texture map boundaries, and possibly the need for multiple textures.
[src:screen-space-reflections/cube-mapping] Computer-aided design (CAD) programs use specular highlights as visual cues to convey a sense of surface curvature when rendering 3D objects.
[src:screen-space-reflections/cube-mapping] However, many CAD programs exhibit problems in sampling specular highlights because the specular lighting computations are only performed at the vertices of the mesh used to represent the object, and interpolation is used to estimate lighting across the surface of the object.
[src:screen-space-reflections/cube-mapping] Problems occur when the mesh vertices are not dense enough, resulting in insufficient sampling of the specular lighting.
[src:screen-space-reflections/cube-mapping] This in turn results in highlights with brightness proportionate to the distance from mesh vertices, ultimately compromising the visual cues that indicate curvature.
[src:screen-space-reflections/cube-mapping] However, this problem cannot be solved by simply creating a denser mesh, as this can greatly reduce the efficiency of object rendering.
[src:screen-space-reflections/cube-mapping] Cube maps provide a fairly straightforward and efficient solution to rendering stable specular highlights.
[src:screen-space-reflections/cube-mapping] Multiple specular highlights can be encoded into a cube map texture, which can then be accessed by interpolating across the surface's reflection vector to supply coordinates.
[src:screen-space-reflections/cube-mapping] Relative to computing lighting at individual vertices, this method provides cleaner results that more accurately represent curvature.
[src:screen-space-reflections/cube-mapping] Another advantage to this method is that it scales well, as additional specular highlights can be encoded into the texture at no increase in the cost of rendering.
[src:screen-space-reflections/cube-mapping] However, this approach is limited in that the light sources must be either distant or infinite lights, although this is usually the case in CAD programs.
[src:screen-space-reflections/cube-mapping] Renders using cubemaps can look better in outdoor scenes.
[src:screen-space-reflections/cube-mapping] Perhaps the most advanced application of cube mapping is to create pre-rendered panoramic sky images which are then rendered by the graphical engine as faces of a cube at practically infinite distance with the view point located in the center of the cube.
[src:screen-space-reflections/cube-mapping] The perspective projection of the cube faces done by the graphics engine undoes the effects of projecting the environment to create the cube map, so that the observer experiences an illusion of being surrounded by the scene which was used to generate the skybox.
[src:screen-space-reflections/cube-mapping] This technique has found a widespread use in video games since it allows designers to add complex (albeit not explorable) environments to a game at almost no performance cost.
[src:screen-space-reflections/cube-mapping] Cube maps can be useful for modelling outdoor illumination accurately.
[src:screen-space-reflections/cube-mapping] Simply modelling sunlight as a single infinite light oversimplifies outdoor illumination and results in unrealistic lighting.
[src:screen-space-reflections/cube-mapping] Although plenty of light does come from the sun, the scattering of rays in the atmosphere causes the whole sky to act as a light source (often referred to as skylight illumination).
[src:screen-space-reflections/cube-mapping] However, by using a cube map, the diffuse contribution from skylight illumination can be captured.
[src:screen-space-reflections/cube-mapping] Unlike environment maps where the reflection vector is used, this method accesses the cube map based on the surface normal vector to provide a fast approximation of the diffuse illumination from the skylight.
[src:screen-space-reflections/cube-mapping] The one downside to this method is that computing cube maps to properly represent a skylight is very complex; one recent process is computing the spherical harmonic basis that best represents the low frequency diffuse illumination from the cube map.
[src:screen-space-reflections/cube-mapping] However, a considerable amount of research has been done to effectively model skylight illumination.
[src:screen-space-reflections/cube-mapping] Basic environment mapping uses a static cube map – although the object can be moved and distorted, the reflected environment stays consistent.
[src:screen-space-reflections/cube-mapping] However, a cube map texture can be consistently updated to represent a dynamically changing environment (for example, trees swaying in the wind).
[src:screen-space-reflections/cube-mapping] A simple yet costly way to generate dynamic reflections involves building the cube maps at runtime for every frame.
[src:screen-space-reflections/cube-mapping] Although this is far less efficient than static mapping because of additional rendering steps, it can still be performed at interactive rates.
[src:screen-space-reflections/cube-mapping] However, this technique does not scale well when multiple reflective objects are present.
[src:screen-space-reflections/cube-mapping] A unique dynamic environment map is usually required for each reflective object.
[src:screen-space-reflections/cube-mapping] Also, further complications are added if reflective objects can reflect each other – dynamic cube maps can be recursively generated, approximating the effects normally generated using raytracing.
[src:screen-space-reflections/cube-mapping] An algorithm for global illumination computation at interactive rates using a cube map data structure, was presented at ICCVG 2002.
[src:screen-space-reflections/cube-mapping] Another application which found widespread use in video games is projective texture mapping.
[src:screen-space-reflections/cube-mapping] It relies on cube maps to project images of an environment onto the surrounding scene; for example, a point light source is tied to a cube map which is a panoramic image shot from inside a lantern cage or a window frame through which the light is filtering.
[src:screen-space-reflections/cube-mapping] This enables a game developer to achieve realistic lighting without having to complicate the scene geometry or resort to expensive real-time shadow volume computations.
[src:screen-space-reflections/cube-mapping] A cube texture indexes six texture maps from 0 to 5 in order: positive X, negative X, positive Y, negative Y, positive Z, negative Z.
[src:screen-space-reflections/cube-mapping] The images are stored with the origin at the lower left of the image.
[src:screen-space-reflections/cube-mapping] The positive X and Y faces must reverse the Z coordinate and the negative Z face must negate the X coordinate.
[src:screen-space-reflections/deferred-shading] In the field of 3D computer graphics, **deferred shading** is a screen-space shading technique that is performed on a second rendering pass, after the vertex and pixel shaders are rendered.
[src:screen-space-reflections/deferred-shading] It was first suggested by Michael Deering in 1988.
[src:screen-space-reflections/deferred-shading] On the first pass of a deferred shader, only data that is required for shading computation is gathered.
[src:screen-space-reflections/deferred-shading] Positions, normals, and materials for each surface are rendered into the geometry buffer (G-buffer) using "render to texture".
[src:screen-space-reflections/deferred-shading] After this, a pixel shader computes the direct and indirect lighting at each pixel using the information of the texture buffers in screen space.
[src:screen-space-reflections/deferred-shading] Screen space directional occlusion can be made part of the deferred shading pipeline to give directionality to shadows and interreflections.
[src:screen-space-reflections/deferred-shading] The primary advantage of deferred shading is the decoupling of scene geometry from lighting.
[src:screen-space-reflections/deferred-shading] Only one geometry pass is required, and each light is only computed for those pixels that it actually affects.
[src:screen-space-reflections/deferred-shading] This gives the ability to render many lights in a scene without a significant performance hit.
[src:screen-space-reflections/deferred-shading] There are some other advantages claimed for the approach.
[src:screen-space-reflections/deferred-shading] These include simpler management of complex lighting resources, ease of managing other complex shader resources, and the simplification of the software rendering pipeline.
[src:screen-space-reflections/deferred-shading] One key disadvantage of deferred rendering is the inability to handle transparency within the algorithm, although this problem is a generic one in Z-buffered scenes and it tends to be handled by delaying and sorting the rendering of transparent portions of the scene.
[src:screen-space-reflections/deferred-shading] Depth peeling can be used to achieve order-independent transparency in deferred rendering, but at the cost of additional batches and g-buffer size.
[src:screen-space-reflections/deferred-shading] Modern hardware, supporting DirectX 10 and later, is often capable of performing batches fast enough to maintain interactive frame rates.
[src:screen-space-reflections/deferred-shading] When order-independent transparency is desired (commonly for consumer applications) deferred shading is no less effective than forward shading using the same technique.
[src:screen-space-reflections/deferred-shading] Another serious disadvantage is the difficulty with using multiple materials.
[src:screen-space-reflections/deferred-shading] It's possible to use many different materials, but it requires more data to be stored in the G-buffer, which is already quite large and takes up a large amount of the memory bandwidth.
[src:screen-space-reflections/deferred-shading] One more disadvantage is that, due to separating the lighting stage from the geometric stage, hardware anti-aliasing does not produce correct results anymore since interpolated subsamples would result in nonsensical position, normal, and tangent attributes.
[src:screen-space-reflections/deferred-shading] Although it is not an edge-smoothing technique, temporal anti-aliasing (used in *Halo: Reach and Unreal Engine*) can also help give edges a smoother appearance.
[src:screen-space-reflections/deferred-shading] DirectX 10 introduced features allowing shaders to access individual samples in multi-sampled render targets (and depth buffers in version 10.1), giving users of this API access to hardware anti-aliasing in deferred shading.
[src:screen-space-reflections/deferred-shading] These features also allow them to correctly apply HDR luminance mapping to anti-aliased edges, where in earlier versions of the API any benefit of anti-aliasing may have been lost.
[src:screen-space-reflections/deferred-shading] Use of the technique has increased in video games because of the control it enables in terms of using a large amount of dynamic lights and reducing the complexity of required shader instructions.
[src:screen-space-reflections/deferred-shading] In comparison to deferred lighting, this technique is not very popular due to high memory size and bandwidth requirements, especially on seventh generation consoles where graphic memory size and bandwidth are limited and often bottlenecks.
[src:screen-space-reflections/deferred-shading] The idea of deferred shading was originally introduced by Michael Deering and his colleagues in a paper published in 1988 titled *The triangle processor and normal vector shader: a VLSI system for high performance graphics*.
[src:screen-space-reflections/deferred-shading] Although the paper never uses the word "deferred", a key concept is introduced; each pixel is shaded only once after depth resolution.
[src:screen-space-reflections/deferred-shading] Deferred shading as we know it today, using G-buffers, was introduced in a paper by Saito and Takahashi in 1990, although they too do not use the word "deferred".
[src:screen-space-reflections/deferred-shading] The first deferred shaded video game was *Shrek*, an Xbox launch title shipped in 2001.
[src:screen-space-reflections/deferred-shading] Around 2004, implementations on commodity graphics hardware started to appear.
[src:screen-space-reflections/deferred-shading] The technique later gained popularity for applications such as video games, finally becoming mainstream around 2008 to 2010.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] polarization, despite being poor reflectors at normal incidence.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] polarization, greatly reducing glare from horizontal surfaces.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] The **Fresnel equations** (or **Fresnel coefficients**) describe the reflection and transmission of light (or electromagnetic radiation in general) when incident on an interface between different optical media.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] They were deduced by French engineer and physicist Augustin-Jean Fresnel (/freɪˈnɛl/) who was the first to understand that light is a transverse wave, when no one realized that the waves were electric and magnetic fields.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] For the first time, polarization could be understood quantitatively, as Fresnel's equations correctly predicted the differing behaviour of waves of the *s* and *p* polarizations incident upon a material interface.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] When light strikes the interface between a medium with refractive index *n*1 and a second medium with refractive index *n*2, both reflection and refraction of the light may occur.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] The Fresnel equations give the ratio of the *reflected* wave's electric field to the incident wave's electric field, and the ratio of the *transmitted* wave's electric field to the incident wave's electric field, for each of two components of polarization.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] (The *magnetic* fields can also be related using similar coefficients.) These ratios are generally complex, describing not only the relative amplitudes but also the phase shifts at the interface.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] The equations assume the interface between the media is flat and that the media are homogeneous and isotropic.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] The incident light is assumed to be a plane wave, which is sufficient to solve any problem since any incident light field can be decomposed into plane waves and polarizations.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] There are two sets of Fresnel coefficients for two different linear polarization components of the incident wave.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] Since any polarization state can be resolved into a combination of two orthogonal linear polarizations, this is sufficient for any problem.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] Likewise, unpolarized (or "randomly polarized") light has an equal amount of power in each of two linear polarizations.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] The s polarization refers to polarization of a wave's electric field *normal* to the plane of incidence (the z direction in the derivation below); then the magnetic field is *in* the plane of incidence.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] The p polarization refers to polarization of the electric field *in* the plane of incidence (the xy plane in the derivation below); then the magnetic field is *normal* to the plane of incidence.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] The names "s" and "p" for the polarization components refer to German "senkrecht" (perpendicular or normal) and "parallel" (parallel to the plane of incidence).
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] Although the reflection and transmission are dependent on polarization, at normal incidence (*θ* = 0) there is no distinction between them so all polarization states are governed by a single set of Fresnel coefficients (and another special case is mentioned below in which that is true).
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] In the diagram, an incident plane wave in the direction of the ray **IO** strikes the interface between two media of refractive indices *n*1 and *n*2 at point **O**.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] Part of the wave is reflected in the direction **OR**, and part refracted in the direction **OT**.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] The angles that the incident, reflected and refracted rays make to the normal of the interface are given as *θ*i, *θ*r and *θ*t, respectively.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] The behavior of light striking the interface is explained by considering the electric and magnetic fields that constitute an electromagnetic wave, and the laws of electromagnetism, as shown below.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] The ratio of waves' electric field (or magnetic field) amplitudes are obtained, but in practice one is more often interested in formulae which determine *power* coefficients, since power (or irradiance) is what can be directly measured at optical frequencies.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] The power of a wave is generally proportional to the square of the electric (or magnetic) field amplitude.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] Note that these are what would be measured right *at* each side of an interface and do not account for attenuation of a wave in an absorbing medium *following* transmission or reflection.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] We assume that the media are non-magnetic (i.e., *μ*1 = *μ*2 = *μ*0), which is typically a good approximation at optical frequencies (and for transparent media at other frequencies).
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] Then the wave impedances are determined solely by the refractive indices *n*1 and *n*2: $Z_{i}={\frac {Z_{0}}{n_{i}}}\,,$ where *Z*0 is the impedance of free space and *i* = 1, 2.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] The second form of each equation is derived from the first by eliminating *θ*t using Snell's law and trigonometric identities.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] Note that all such intensities are measured in terms of a wave's irradiance in the direction normal to the interface; this is also what is measured in typical experiments.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] This complication can be ignored in the case of the reflection coefficient, since cos *θ*i = cos *θ*r, so that the ratio of reflected to incident irradiance in the wave's direction is the same as in the direction normal to the interface.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] Although these relationships describe the basic physics, in many practical applications one is concerned with "natural light" that can be described as unpolarized.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] For low-precision applications involving unpolarized light, such as computer graphics, rather than rigorously computing the effective reflection coefficient for each angle, Schlick's approximation is often used.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] For the case of normal incidence, *θ*i = *θ*t = 0, and there is no distinction between s and p polarization.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] For common glass (*n*2 ≈ 1.5) surrounded by air (*n*1 = 1), the power reflectance at normal incidence can be seen to be about 4%, or 8% accounting for both sides of a glass pane.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] At a dielectric interface from *n*1 to *n*2, there is a particular angle of incidence at which *R*p goes to zero and a p-polarised incident wave is purely refracted, thus all reflected light is s-polarised.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] This angle is known as Brewster's angle, and is around 56° for *n*1 = 1 and *n*2 = 1.5 (typical glass).
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] When light travelling in a denser medium strikes the surface of a less dense medium (i.e., *n*1 > *n*2), beyond a particular incidence angle known as the *critical angle*, all light is reflected and *R*s = *R*p = 1.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] This phenomenon, known as total internal reflection, occurs at incidence angles for which Snell's law predicts that the sine of the angle of refraction would exceed unity (whereas in fact sin *θ* ≤ 1 for all real *θ*).
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] For glass with *n* = 1.5 surrounded by air, the critical angle is approximately 42°.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] Reflection at 45° incidence is very commonly used for making 90° turns.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] This can be used to either verify the consistency of the measurements of *R*s and *R*p, or to derive one of them when the other is known.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] This relationship is only valid for the simple case of a single plane interface between two homogeneous materials, not for films on substrates, where a more complex analysis is required.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] Measurements of *R*s and *R*p at 45° can be used to estimate the reflectivity at normal incidence.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] The "average of averages" obtained by calculating first the arithmetic as well as the geometric average of *R*s and *R*p, and then averaging these two averages again arithmetically, gives a value for *R*0 with an error of less than about 3% for most common optical materials.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] This is useful because measurements at normal incidence can be difficult to achieve in an experimental setup since the incoming beam and the detector will obstruct each other.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] However, since the dependence of *R*s and *R*p on the angle of incidence for angles below 10° is very small, a measurement at about 5° will usually be a good approximation for normal incidence, while allowing for a separation of the incoming and reflected beam.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] The above equations relating powers (which could be measured with a photometer for instance) are derived from the Fresnel equations which solve the physical problem in terms of electromagnetic field complex amplitudes, i.e., considering phase shifts in addition to their amplitudes.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] Those underlying equations supply generally complex-valued ratios of those EM fields and may take several different forms, depending on the formalism used.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] The complex amplitude coefficients for reflection and transmission are usually represented by lower case *r* and *t* (whereas the power coefficients are capitalized).
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] As before, we are assuming the magnetic permeability, *µ* of both media to be equal to the permeability of free space *µ*0 as is essentially true of all dielectrics at optical frequencies.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] In the following equations and graphs, we adopt the following conventions.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] The transmission coefficient *t* is the ratio of the transmitted wave's complex electric field amplitude to that of the incident wave, for either polarization.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] The equations consider a plane wave incident on a plane interface at angle of incidence $\theta _{\mathrm {i} }$ , a wave reflected at angle $\theta _{\mathrm {r} }=\theta _{\mathrm {i} }$ , and a wave transmitted at angle $\theta _{\mathrm {t} }$ .
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] In the case of an interface into an absorbing material (where *n* is complex) or total internal reflection, the angle of transmission does not generally evaluate to a real number.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] In that case, however, meaningful results can be obtained using formulations of these relationships in which trigonometric functions and geometric angles are avoided; the inhomogeneous waves launched into the second medium cannot be described using a single propagation angle.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] For the case where the magnetic permeabilities are non-negligible, the equations change such that every appearance of $n_{i}$ is replaced by $n_{i}/\mu _{i}$ (for both $i=1,2$ ).
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] One can write very similar equations applying to the ratio of the waves' magnetic fields, but comparison of the electric fields is more conventional.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] On the other hand, calculation of the power transmission coefficient T is less straightforward, since the light travels in different directions in the two media.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] What's more, the wave impedances in the two media differ; power (irradiance) is given by the square of the electric field amplitude *divided by* the characteristic impedance of the medium (or by the square of the magnetic field *multiplied by* the characteristic impedance).
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] The introduced factor of ⁠*n*2/*n*1⁠ is the reciprocal of the ratio of the media's wave impedances.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] The cos(*θ*) factors adjust the waves' powers so they are reckoned *in the direction* normal to the interface, for both the incident and transmitted waves, so that full power transmission corresponds to *T* = 1.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] In the case of total internal reflection where the power transmission T is zero, t nevertheless describes the electric field (including its phase) just beyond the interface.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] This is an evanescent field which does not propagate as a wave (thus *T* = 0) but has nonzero values very close to the interface.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] The phase shift of the reflected wave on total internal reflection can similarly be obtained from the phase angles of *r*p and *r*s (whose magnitudes are unity in this case).
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] These phase shifts are different for *s* and *p* waves, which is the well-known principle by which total internal reflection is used to effect polarization transformations.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] These formulas are known respectively as *Fresnel's sine law* and *Fresnel's tangent law*.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] Although at normal incidence these expressions reduce to 0/0, one can see that they yield the correct results in the limit as *θ*i → 0.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] When light makes multiple reflections between two or more parallel surfaces, the multiple beams of light generally interfere with one another, resulting in net transmission and reflection amplitudes that depend on the light's wavelength.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] The interference, however, is seen only when the surfaces are at distances comparable to or smaller than the light's coherence length, which for ordinary white light is few micrometers; it can be much larger for light from a laser.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] An example of interference between reflections is the iridescent colours seen in a soap bubble or in thin oil films on water.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] Applications include Fabry–Pérot interferometers, antireflection coatings, and optical filters.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] A quantitative analysis of these effects is based on the Fresnel equations, but with additional calculations to account for interference.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] The transfer-matrix method, or Rouard's recursive method can be used to solve multiple-surface problems.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] In 1808, Étienne-Louis Malus discovered that when a ray of light was reflected off a non-metallic surface at the appropriate angle, it behaved like *one* of the two rays emerging from a doubly-refractive calcite crystal.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] He later coined the term *polarization* to describe this behavior.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] In 1815, the dependence of the polarizing angle on the refractive index was determined experimentally by David Brewster.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] In 1821, however, Augustin-Jean Fresnel derived results equivalent to his sine and tangent laws (above), by modeling light waves as transverse elastic waves with vibrations perpendicular to what had previously been called the plane of polarization.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] The experimental confirmation was reported in a "postscript" to the work in which Fresnel first revealed his theory that light waves, including "unpolarized" waves, were *purely* transverse.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] Details of Fresnel's derivation, including the modern forms of the sine law and tangent law, were given later, in a memoir read to the French Academy of Sciences in January 1823.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] That derivation combined conservation of energy with continuity of the *tangential* vibration at the interface, but failed to allow for any condition on the *normal* component of vibration.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] The first derivation from *electromagnetic* principles was given by Hendrik Lorentz in 1875.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] In the same memoir of January 1823, Fresnel found that for angles of incidence greater than the critical angle, his formulas for the reflection coefficients (*r*s and *r*p) gave complex values with unit magnitudes.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] Noting that the magnitude, as usual, represented the ratio of peak amplitudes, he guessed that the argument represented the phase shift, and verified the hypothesis experimentally.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] Thus he finally had a quantitative theory for what we now call the *Fresnel rhomb* — a device that he had been using in experiments, in one form or another, since 1817 (see *Fresnel rhomb § History*).
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] The success of the complex reflection coefficient inspired James MacCullagh and Augustin-Louis Cauchy, beginning in 1836, to analyze reflection from metals by using the Fresnel equations with a complex refractive index.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] Thus Fresnel's interpretation of the complex values of his reflection coefficients marked the confluence of several streams of his research and, arguably, the essential completion of his reconstruction of physical optics on the transverse-wave hypothesis (see *Augustin-Jean Fresnel*).
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] Here we systematically derive the above relations from electromagnetic premises.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] In order to compute meaningful Fresnel coefficients, we must assume that the medium is (approximately) linear and homogeneous.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] For vacuum, these have the values *ϵ*0 and *μ*0, respectively.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] Hence we define the *relative* permittivity (or dielectric constant) *ϵ*rel = *ϵ*/*ϵ*0, and the *relative* permeability *μ*rel = *μ*/*μ*0.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] In optics it is common to assume that the medium is non-magnetic, so that *μ*rel = 1.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] For ferromagnetic materials at radio/microwave frequencies, larger values of *μ*rel must be taken into account.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] But, for optically transparent media, and for all other materials at optical frequencies (except possible metamaterials), *μ*rel is indeed very close to 1; that is, *μ* ≈ *μ*0.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] In optics, one usually knows the refractive index *n* of the medium, which is the ratio of the speed of light in vacuum (c) to the speed of light in the medium.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] In the analysis of partial reflection and transmission, one is also interested in the electromagnetic wave impedance Z, which is the ratio of the amplitude of **E** to the amplitude of **H**.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] It is therefore desirable to express *n* and Z in terms of *ϵ* and *μ*, and thence to relate Z to *n*.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] The last-mentioned relation, however, will make it convenient to derive the reflection coefficients in terms of the wave *admittance* Y, which is the reciprocal of the wave impedance Z.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] In the case of *uniform plane sinusoidal* waves, the wave impedance or admittance is known as the *intrinsic* impedance or admittance of the medium.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] This case is the one for which the Fresnel coefficients are to be derived.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] The value of the expression is unchanged if the position **r** varies in a direction normal to **k**; hence **k** *is normal to the wavefronts*.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] To advance the phase by the angle *ϕ*, we replace *ωt* by *ωt* + *ϕ* (that is, we replace −*ωt* by −*ωt* − *ϕ*), with the result that the (complex) field is multiplied by *e−iϕ*.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] So a phase *advance* is equivalent to multiplication by a complex constant with a *negative* argument.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] This becomes more obvious when the field (**1**) is factored as **Ek** *e**i***k**⋅**r***e**−iωt*, where the last factor contains the time-dependence.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] That factor also implies that differentiation w.r.t. time corresponds to multiplication by *−iω*.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] If the argument of *e**i*(⋯) is to be constant, *ℓ* must increase at the velocity $\omega /k\,,\,$ known as the *phase velocity* (*v*p).
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] As usual, we drop the time-dependent factor *e*−*iωt*, which is understood to multiply every complex field quantity.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] Taking the magnitude equations and substituting from (**2**), we obtain ${\begin{aligned}\mu cH&=nE\\\epsilon cE&=nH\,,\end{aligned}}$ where H and E are the magnitudes of **H** and **E**.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] Dividing the second result by the first gives $n={\sqrt {\mu _{\text{rel}}\epsilon _{\text{rel}}}}\,.$ For a *non-magnetic* medium (the usual case), this becomes ⁠ $n={\sqrt {\epsilon _{\text{rel}}}}$ ⁠.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] (Taking the reciprocal of (**5**), we find that the intrinsic *impedance* is ${\textstyle Z={\sqrt {\mu /\epsilon }}}$ .
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] In vacuum this takes the value ${\textstyle Z_{0}={\sqrt {\mu _{0}/\epsilon _{0}}}\,\approx 377\,\Omega \,,}$ known as the impedance of free space.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] In Cartesian coordinates (*x*, *y*, *z*), let the region *y* < 0 have refractive index *n*1, intrinsic admittance *Y*1, etc., and let the region *y* > 0 have refractive index *n*2, intrinsic admittance *Y*2, etc.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] Then the *xz* plane is the interface, and the *y* axis is normal to the interface (see diagram).
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] Let **i** and **j** (in bold roman type) be the unit vectors in the *x* and *y* directions, respectively.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] Let the plane of incidence be the *xy* plane (the plane of the page), with the angle of incidence *θ*i measured from **j** towards **i**.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] Let the angle of refraction, measured in the same sense, be *θ*t, where the subscript *t* stands for *transmitted* (reserving *r* for *reflected*).
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] In the absence of Doppler shifts, *ω* does not change on reflection or refraction.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] Hence, by (**2**), the magnitude of the wave vector is proportional to the refractive index.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] So, for a given *ω*, if we *redefine* k as the magnitude of the wave vector in the *reference* medium (for which *n* = 1), then the wave vector has magnitude *n*1*k* in the first medium (region *y* < 0 in the diagram) and magnitude *n*2*k* in the second medium.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] For the *s* polarization, the **E** field is parallel to the *z* axis and may therefore be described by its component in the *z* direction.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] Let the reflection and transmission coefficients be *r*s and *t*s, respectively.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] Under the sign convention used in this article, a positive reflection or transmission coefficient is one that preserves the direction of the *transverse* field, meaning (in this context) the field normal to the plane of incidence.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] For the *s* polarization, that means the **E** field.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] If the incident, reflected, and transmitted **E** fields (in the above equations) are in the *z*-direction ("out of the page"), then the respective **H** fields are in the directions of the red arrows, since **k**, **E**, **H** form a right-handed orthogonal triad.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] The **H** fields may therefore be described by their components in the directions of those arrows, denoted by *H*i, *H*r, *H*t.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] For the *p* polarization, the incident, reflected, and transmitted **E** fields are parallel to the red arrows and may therefore be described by their components in the directions of those arrows.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] Let those components be *E*i, *E*r, *E*t (redefining the symbols for the new context).
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] Let the reflection and transmission coefficients be *r*p and *t*p.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] If the **E** fields are in the directions of the red arrows, then, in order for **k**, **E**, **H** to form a right-handed orthogonal triad, the respective **H** fields must be in the −*z*-direction ("into the page") and may therefore be described by their components in that direction.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] This is consistent with the adopted sign convention, namely that a positive reflection or transmission coefficient is one that preserves the direction of the transverse field (the **H** field in the case of the *p* polarization).
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] So, for the incident, reflected, and transmitted **H** fields, let the respective components in the −*z*-direction be *H*i, *H*r, *H*t.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] At *grazing incidence* (*θ*i → 90°), we again have cos *θ*i → 0, hence *r*p → −1 and *t*p → 0.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] Comparing (**23**) and (**24**) with (**15**) and (**16**), we see that at *normal* incidence, under the adopted sign convention, the transmission coefficients for the two polarizations are equal, whereas the reflection coefficients have equal magnitudes but opposite signs.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] While this clash of signs is a disadvantage of the convention, the attendant advantage is that the signs agree at *grazing* incidence.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] The *Poynting vector* for a wave is a vector whose component in any direction is the *irradiance* (power per unit area) of that wave on a surface perpendicular to that direction.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] For a plane sinusoidal wave the Poynting vector is ⁠1/2⁠‍Re{**E** × **H**∗}, where **E** and **H** are due *only* to the wave in question, and the asterisk denotes complex conjugation.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] Note that when comparing the powers of two such waves in the same medium and with the same cos *θ*, the impedance and geometric factors mentioned above are identical and cancel out.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] But in computing the power *transmission* (below), these factors must be taken into account.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] The simplest way to obtain the power transmission coefficient (*transmissivity*, the ratio of transmitted power to incident power *in the direction normal to the interface*, i.e. the y direction) is to use *R* + *T* = 1 (conservation of energy).
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] In the case of an interface between two lossless media (for which ϵ and μ are *real* and positive), one can obtain these results directly using the squared magnitudes of the amplitude transmission coefficients that we found earlier in equations (**14**) and (**22**).
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] But, for given amplitude (as noted above), the component of the Poynting vector in the y direction is proportional to the geometric factor cos *θ* and inversely proportional to the wave impedance Z.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] The last two equations apply only to lossless dielectrics, and only at incidence angles smaller than the critical angle (beyond which, of course, *T* = 0).
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] From equations (**4**) and (**5**), we see that two dissimilar media will have the same refractive index, but different admittances, if the ratio of their permeabilities is the inverse of the ratio of their permittivities.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] When extended to spherical reflection or scattering, this results in the Kerker effect for Mie scattering.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] Since the Fresnel equations were developed for optics, they are usually given for non-magnetic materials.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] The power transmissions can then be found from *T* = 1 − *R*.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] For equal permeabilities (e.g., non-magnetic media), if *θ*i and *θ*t are *complementary*, we can substitute sin *θ*t for cos *θ*i, and sin *θ*i for cos *θ*t, so that the numerator in equation (**31**) becomes *n*2‍sin *θ*t − *n*1‍sin *θ*i, which is zero (by Snell's law).
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] Hence *r*p = 0 and only the s-polarized component is reflected.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] This is what happens at the Brewster angle.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] Although it is not encountered in practice, the equations can also apply to the case of two media with a common permittivity but different refractive indices due to different permeabilities.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] From equations (**4**) and (**5**), if *ϵ* is fixed instead of *μ*, then Y becomes *inversely* proportional to n, with the result that the subscripts 1 and 2 in equations (**29**) to (**38**) are interchanged (due to the additional step of multiplying the numerator and denominator by *n*1*n*2).
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] Hence, in (**29**) and (**31**), the expressions for *r*s and *r*p in terms of refractive indices will be interchanged, so that Brewster's angle (**39**) will give *r*s = 0 instead of *r*p = 0, and any beam reflected at that angle will be p-polarized instead of s-polarized.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] Similarly, Fresnel's sine law will apply to the p polarization instead of the s polarization, and his tangent law to the s polarization instead of the p polarization.
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] This switch of polarizations has an analog in the old mechanical theory of light waves (see *§ History*, above).
[src:screen-space-reflections/fresnel-equations] Thus the condition of equal permittivities and unequal permeabilities, although not realistic, is of some historical interest.
[src:screen-space-reflections/ray-marching] The technique dates back to at least the 1980s; the 1989 paper "Hypertexture" by Ken Perlin contains an early example of a ray marching method.
[src:screen-space-reflections/ray-marching] In **sphere tracing**, or **sphere-assisted ray marching** an intersection point is approximated between the ray and a surface defined by a signed distance function (SDF).
[src:screen-space-reflections/ray-marching] The SDF is evaluated for each iteration in order to be able take as large steps as possible without missing any part of the surface.
[src:screen-space-reflections/ray-marching] A threshold is used to cancel further iteration when a point has reached that is close enough to the surface.
[src:screen-space-reflections/ray-marching] As powerful GPU hardware became more widely available, this method was popularized by the demoscene and Inigo Quilez, co-creator of Shadertoy.
[src:screen-space-reflections/ray-marching] For simple scenes with basic 3D shapes, ray marching does not have many benefits over ray tracing (which finds intersections without marching through the space).
[src:screen-space-reflections/ray-marching] Strengths of SDF ray marching are, for example, when morphing shapes, approximating soft shadows, repetition of geometry, and algorithmically defined scenes.
[src:screen-space-reflections/ray-marching] Signed distance functions exist for many primitive 3D shapes.
[src:screen-space-reflections/ray-marching] They can be combined using mathematical operations like modulo and booleans to form more complex surfaces.
[src:screen-space-reflections/ray-marching] For instance, taking the modulus of an SDF's input coordinates tiles its volume across all of space, and taking the maximum of two SDFs gives their volumes' surface of intersection.
[src:screen-space-reflections/ray-marching] Because SDFs can be defined for many fractals, sphere tracing is often used for 3D fractal rendering.
[src:screen-space-reflections/ray-marching] A similar technique to sphere-assisted ray marching, the use of cubes and taxicab distance can be used to render voxel volumes.
[src:screen-space-reflections/ray-marching] In volumetric ray marching, each ray is traced so that color and/or density can be sampled along the ray and then be combined into a final pixel color.
[src:screen-space-reflections/ray-marching] This is often used for example when rendering clouds or 3D medical scans.
[src:screen-space-reflections/ray-marching] When rendering screen space effects, such as screen space reflection (SSR) and screen space shadows, rays are traced using G-buffers, where depth and surface normal data is stored per each 2D pixel.
[src:screen-space-reflections/reflection-computer-graphics] Accurate reflections are commonly computed using ray tracing whereas approximate reflections can usually be computed faster by using simpler methods such as environment mapping.
[src:screen-space-reflections/reflection-computer-graphics] Reflections on shiny surfaces like wood or tile can add to the photorealistic effects of a 3D rendering.
[src:screen-space-reflections/reflection-computer-graphics] For rendering environment reflections there exist many techniques that differ in precision, computational and implementation complexity.
[src:screen-space-reflections/reflection-computer-graphics] Combination of these techniques are also possible.
[src:screen-space-reflections/reflection-computer-graphics] Image order rendering algorithms based on tracing rays of light, such as ray tracing or path tracing, typically compute accurate reflections on general surfaces, including multiple reflections and self reflections.
[src:screen-space-reflections/reflection-computer-graphics] However these algorithms are generally still too computationally expensive for real time rendering (even though specialized hardware exists, such as Nvidia RTX) and require a different rendering approach from typically used rasterization.
[src:screen-space-reflections/reflection-computer-graphics] Reflections on planar surfaces, such as planar mirrors or water surfaces, can be computed simply and accurately in real time with two pass rendering — one for the viewer, one for the view in the mirror, usually with the help of stencil buffer.
[src:screen-space-reflections/reflection-computer-graphics] Some older video games used a trick to achieve this effect with one pass rendering by putting the whole mirrored scene behind a transparent plane representing the mirror.
[src:screen-space-reflections/reflection-computer-graphics] Reflections on non-planar (curved) surfaces are more challenging for real time rendering.
[src:screen-space-reflections/reflection-computer-graphics] Mirrors are usually almost 100% reflective.
[src:screen-space-reflections/reflection-computer-graphics] Normal (nonmetallic) objects reflect light and colors in the original color of the object being reflected.
[src:screen-space-reflections/reflection-computer-graphics] Metallic objects reflect lights and colors altered by the color of the metallic object itself.
[src:screen-space-reflections/reflection-computer-graphics] Many materials are imperfect reflectors, where the reflections are blurred to various degrees due to surface roughness that scatters the rays of the reflections.
[src:screen-space-reflections/reflection-computer-graphics] Fully glossy reflection, shows highlights from light sources, but does not show a clear reflection from objects.
[src:screen-space-reflections/reflection-computer-graphics] The *wet floor effect* is a graphic effects technique popular in conjunction with Web 2.0 style pages, particularly in logos.
[src:screen-space-reflections/reflection-computer-graphics] The effect can be done manually or created with an auxiliary tool which can be installed to create the effect automatically.
[src:screen-space-reflections/reflection-computer-graphics] Unlike a standard computer reflection (and the Java water effect popular in first-generation web graphics), the wet floor effect involves a gradient and often a slant in the reflection, so that the mirrored image appears to be hovering over or resting on a wet floor.
[src:screen-space-reflections/screen-space] In 3D computer graphics, the **image plane**, also called **screen space**, is that plane in the world which corresponds to the display monitor used to view the image that is being rendered.
[src:screen-space-reflections/screen-space] If one makes the analogy of taking a photograph to rendering a 3D image, the surface of the film (or the image sensor) is the image plane.
[src:screen-space-reflections/screen-space] In this case, the viewing transformation is a projection that maps the world onto the image plane.
[src:screen-space-reflections/screen-space] A rectangular region of this plane, called the viewing window or viewport, maps to the monitor.
[src:screen-space-reflections/screen-space] This establishes the mapping between pixels on the monitor and points (or rather, rays) in the 3D world.
[src:screen-space-reflections/screen-space] The plane is not usually an actual geometric object in a 3D scene, but instead is usually a collection of target coordinates or dimensions that are used during the rasterization process so the final output can be displayed as intended on the physical screen.
[src:screen-space-reflections/screen-space] In optics, the image plane is the plane that contains the object's projected image, and lies beyond the back focal plane.
